<div class="badge"><span class="badge-dot"></span>FRACTIONAL CMO · TEAM BUILD</div>
<h1 class="hero-h">Building a marketing team with a <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">fractional CMO.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">One of the highest-leverage things a fractional CMO does is build the team. The 2026 AI-native team is 30-50% leaner than the 2020 norm while producing more — and the hiring sequence + role design make or break it. Here's the team-build playbook.</p>
</div></div>


<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The frame</span>
<h2 class="h2">Why team design matters more than individual hires</h2>
<p class="body">Most companies that get team-build wrong made one of two errors. Either they hired the wrong-shaped role for their stage (specialist when they needed generalist, or vice versa), or they over-hired because the role design assumed the 2020 operating model that AI agents have since collapsed.</p>
<p class="body">A fractional CMO who is genuinely AI-native designs around the work the team will actually do in 2026, not the work a 2020 marketing team did. The result is a leaner, more capable team — and a lower fixed-cost base that survives changes in revenue trajectory.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The hiring sequence</span>
<h2 class="h2">Who to hire first (by company stage)</h2>
<h3 class="h3">Stage 1: $1M-$3M revenue, founder-led marketing, fractional CMO incoming</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>First hire:</strong> Marketing manager / generalist ($75K-$110K). Owns execution across the funnel. Works with fractional CMO on strategy + priorities.</li>
<li><strong>Augment with:</strong> AI agent platform (replaces SDR + admin work). Content production contractor or agency for long-form. Designer contractor as needed.</li>
<li><strong>Total marketing headcount:</strong> 1 FTE + fractional CMO leadership + AI + contractors.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Stage 2: $3M-$10M revenue, building real function</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Add:</strong> Demand gen / paid specialist ($85K-$130K) OR content lead ($85K-$130K) depending on which funnel stage is the constraint.</li>
<li><strong>Augment with:</strong> AI workflows for content production, lead nurture, reporting. Specialist contractors for video, design, SEO.</li>
<li><strong>Total marketing headcount:</strong> 2 FTE + fractional CMO + AI + contractor stack.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Stage 3: $10M-$25M revenue, scaling function</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Add:</strong> Marketing operations lead ($95K-$140K) and the missing demand or content role.</li>
<li><strong>Augment with:</strong> Maturing AI agent workflows; product marketing specialist for some companies.</li>
<li><strong>Total marketing headcount:</strong> 3-4 FTE + fractional CMO + AI + contractor stack.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Stage 4: $25M+ revenue, transition to full-time CMO</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Fractional CMO helps recruit the full-time CMO replacement and transitions out over 60-90 days.</li>
<li>Team has typically grown to 5-8 FTE plus full AI agent stack and core agency relationships.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">2026 team design</span>
<h2 class="h2">Headcount-vs-output benchmarks</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Revenue stage</th><th>2020 norm</th><th>2026 AI-native</th><th>Output delta</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>$3M-$10M</td><td>3-5 FTE marketing</td><td>1-2 FTE + AI + contractors</td><td>~equivalent</td></tr>
<tr><td>$10M-$25M</td><td>5-9 FTE marketing</td><td>3-4 FTE + AI + contractors</td><td>~equivalent or better</td></tr>
<tr><td>$25M-$50M</td><td>8-15 FTE marketing</td><td>5-8 FTE + AI + contractors</td><td>~equivalent or better</td></tr>
<tr><td>$50M-$100M</td><td>15-30 FTE marketing</td><td>10-18 FTE + AI</td><td>~equivalent</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The savings show up in OpEx, not on the marketing P&L line.</strong> A 2026 AI-native marketing team at $10M-$25M revenue runs $400K-$650K lower fully-loaded than its 2020 equivalent, while shipping equivalent output. That's pure operating margin improvement.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Role design changes</span>
<h2 class="h2">Roles that AI absorbed, eliminated, or transformed</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Eliminated or absorbed:</strong> Marketing automation specialist (built into platforms). SDR for marketing-qualified leads (agent absorbs). Junior copywriter (AI-drafted + human-reviewed). Reporting analyst (automated dashboards).</li>
<li><strong>Transformed:</strong> Content lead (now owns AI content production workflow + strategy + editorial standards, not solo writing). Paid media coordinator (now AI-assisted optimization + creative iteration, less manual). Designer (now system + template + AI workflow design, less individual asset production).</li>
<li><strong>Unchanged or more important:</strong> Marketing leadership (CMO/fractional CMO/marketing manager). Brand and creative direction. Customer/account research. Sales-marketing alignment. Vendor management for specialist work.</li>
<li><strong>New roles:</strong> Marketing AI lead / marketing engineer — owns the agent stack, prompt design, workflow automation. Often a hybrid IC role that some companies don't yet have but should.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What to outsource</span>
<h2 class="h2">In-house vs contractor vs agency</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Keep in-house:</strong> Strategy, brand, customer/account intelligence, AI workflow ownership, core demand-gen execution, sales-marketing alignment.</li>
<li><strong>Contractors:</strong> Specialized writing (long-form, technical), video production, photography, specialized SEO work, design refresh sprints.</li>
<li><strong>Agencies (often unnecessary for $3M-$25M):</strong> Paid media (only if scale justifies — most don't), PR, large brand projects, niche specialist work.</li>
<li><strong>The 2026 trend:</strong> Less agency dependency. AI agents + better in-house tools mean specialists can produce work that used to require agencies. Use agencies for true specialist or scale needs; not as a default.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Common mistakes</span>
<h2 class="h2">Five team-build mistakes a fractional CMO helps avoid</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Over-hiring at the wrong stage.</strong> Hiring 4 marketing FTE at $3M ARR when 1 + AI + contractors is right. Fixed cost burden you can't reverse easily.</li>
<li><strong>2. Wrong-shaped first hire.</strong> Hiring a senior specialist when a generalist is what the stage needs (or vice versa). Fractional CMO calibrates to actual need.</li>
<li><strong>3. Replicating the 2020 org chart.</strong> Some founders hire "what worked at my last company in 2018" — the AI-native team design has changed since.</li>
<li><strong>4. Skipping the marketing engineer / AI lead role.</strong> At $10M+ revenue, having no one owning the agent stack means the agents drift and degrade.</li>
<li><strong>5. Agency dependency that doesn't scale.</strong> $25K/month in agency fees buying work an in-house team + AI could produce for $8K-$12K of marginal cost.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>


